BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:MmpUBoUjL5yqBdwgUxVT8
SUMMARY:EMBODIED ALTARS DANCE CLASS
DTSTAMP:20260205T082836Z
DTSTART:20260217T023000Z
DESCRIPTION:EMBODIED ALTARS is an all-levels dance class hosted by Daybreak
	 Star Radio. Designed by Indigenous Chicana artist and El Sueño director\,
	 Alicia Mullikin. Dancers will utilize Indigenous principles within moveme
	nt\, meditation\, and song as a way to practice gratitude\, honor the land
	\, and recognize their ancestors. The class is for those who are intereste
	d in reflection\, intention setting\, and a discovery of their own stories
	. No dance experience necessary. \n\nClass Time: Mondays\, 6:30-8PM \n\nNo
	 class 9/15/25\n\nNo class 10/13/25\n\nVenue: Daybreak Star Indian Cultura
	l Center\n\n5011 Bernie Whitebear Way\,\n\nSeattle\, WA 98199 \n\nSliding 
	Scale: $10-$20\\* per class. Sign Up Now! \n\n  \n\nThis venue is ADA acce
	ssible w/ ADA bathrooms and a wheelchair lift to the second floor. Class w
	ill be held in the ballroom space\, this area has 5 ADA parking spaces.\n\
	nThere are an additional 25 parking spots in our lot\, there is ample park
	ing space along the road leading up to Daybreak star as well as the Discov
	ery Park North Parking lot. \n\nWhat to bring: water\, comfortable clothes
	 to dance in\, journal\, your personal identity\, a desire to explore new 
	pathways and an open mind/heart. \n\nHosted at Daybreak Star Indian Cultur
	al Center\n\nProduced by United Indians of All Tribes Foundation\n\nIn Par
	tnership with El Sueno Dance & Daybreak Star Radio\n\n“Indigenize the Airw
	aves” “Art. Culture. Reclamation.” \n\n\\*Talk to us about BIPOC and Queer
	/LGBTQIA2S\\+ Scholorships\\* \n\nPlease contact @el.sueno.dance on IG for
	 private conversations about this topic.\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/embodied-altars-dance-cla
	ss/16539055/2026-02-16T00
LOCATION:Daybreak Star Indian Cultural Center\, 5011 Bernie Whitebear Way\,
	 Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:_zGawwULcfZ_oThIsiH-P
SUMMARY:Cherub
DTSTAMP:20260205T082836Z
DTSTART:20260217T030000Z
DESCRIPTION:Beyond the fog of burning blunts\, the sea of whiskey\, and for
	est of empties\, you'll find two sweethearts in a Nashville garage. Just a
	s they were yesterday\, the day before that\, and years prior. Searching f
	or the perfect combination of string plucking\, button pushing\, and knob 
	turning to craft the ideal sound to make you forget your world and step in
	to theirs. The aforementioned sweethearts are Jordan Kelley and Jason Hube
	r\; known to most as "Cherub."   It all began in 2010 at Middle Tennessee 
	State University. The two met as Jason was playing around town with local 
	bands and Jordan was crafting what would become known as their first album
	\, Man of the Hour. A few years later\, it was the song "Doses & Mimosas" 
	that caught the attention of the public and gained the interest of Columbi
	a Records\, who signed the duo in 2013. Their four-year major label run br
	ought their fans two LPs\, Year of the Caprese and Bleed Gold Piss Excelle
	nce\, while also sending them around the world playing festivals such as L
	ollapalooza\, Bonnaroo\, Glastonbury\, Outside Lands\, Osheaga\, Summer Ca
	mp\, Summer Sonic\, and headlining four US tours. Now\, a double platinum 
	record and over 300 million Spotify streams later\, the bond between them 
	remains "unfuckwithable\," as they construct their newest batch of genre-d
	efying anthems. Their latest chapter sees Cherub sharpening their stakes w
	ith their brand-new album Everything Changes and That's OK\, anchored by t
	he high-gloss singles "Long Story Short\," "Motion\," and "Crime Scene." O
	n "Long Story Short" they joined forces with Louis Futon in the producer's
	 chair\, turning their garage-grown vibe into something polished and immed
	iate. "Motion" leans into their dreamy electronic pop roots\, while "Crime
	 Scene" lands with a darker edge\, proving they still know how to flip the
	 switch. As Huber put it earlier this year: "This record is us embracing w
	here we've been and moving fast toward where we want to go."  From the str
	eets of Bangkok\, to the dive bars of Nashville\, Cherub has been drawing 
	inspiration from everything around them. There's no doubt that the latest 
	Cherub efforts will win over their existing audience and draw new listener
	s to their established brand of debauchery. From your ears to your heart\,
	 like searching for room on their bodies for a new tattoo\, they'll find a
	 way.\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/cherub/17760052/2026-02-1
	6T00
LOCATION:The Showbox\, 1426 1st Ave.\, Seattle\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
